title art education for the blind

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:10.030
An art therapist prepares materials for
an art workshop. When beginning an art 

00:00:10.030 --> 00:00:11.769
project with students

00:00:11.769 --> 00:00:16.249
teachers are encouraged to offer of a
variety of materials

00:00:16.249 --> 00:00:17.130
beads,

00:00:17.130 --> 00:00:20.210
feathers, wood, 

00:00:20.210 --> 00:00:21.019
old scarves, 

00:00:21.019 --> 00:00:26.359
even tape could make this creative
experience a fun one.  There's sound, 

00:00:26.359 --> 00:00:31.460
it's tactile and the color will
elicit allot of imagination so there's a

00:00:31.460 --> 00:00:36.600
lot of people with vision impairment do have color concepts even if they're completely blind.

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:39.560
Students sit around a table working on
our projects.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:43.920
Then art therapist Jennifer Drower
speaks.  Many students choose the

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:47.800
materials they want to use. It's an
important part of art making

00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:51.400
especially for students who are blind or
have low vision.

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:52.720
With these kids

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:55.300
so many decisions are made for them

00:00:55.300 --> 00:00:57.940
it's so important for them to be able to choose 

00:00:57.940 --> 00:00:59.820
want they want to do,

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:02.100
they're able to make choices

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:07.570
and authentic choices that will help them
to best express whatever it is that they want to express.

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:12.740
It's important to have items in separate
containers

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:14.630
so they can then discern

00:01:14.630 --> 00:01:16.460
what's what, it gives it a boundary.

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:19.500
So they have a focus point for what
they want and they know where to go.

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:22.349
Now a series of shots

00:01:22.349 --> 00:01:26.399
a student manipulates clay, another
places colored shapes on a white sheet

00:01:26.399 --> 00:01:31.189
of paper, another student in a wheelchair
applies paint with a brush to a canvas

00:01:31.189 --> 00:01:32.750
on an easel.

00:01:32.750 --> 00:01:36.550
ms dreylinger students can choose to
make a heart that relates to their

00:01:36.550 --> 00:01:38.040
museum experience

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:42.570
Then Ms. Drower. Students can choose to make art that relates to their museum experience, a life experience,or one that comes from their imaginations.

00:01:42.570 --> 00:01:47.520
Talking or writing about their artworks
is another way to spark creativity.

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:52.030
Freedom of expression is the most
important element in this exercise and

00:01:52.030 --> 00:01:56.590
one that helps foster self esteem
especially for those who have been blind

00:01:56.590 --> 00:02:03.509
since birth. It is a vehicle in which one sees
oneself reflected back. 

00:02:03.509 --> 00:02:04.490
It builds a sense of self 

00:02:08.149 --> 00:02:10.309
that is evidence of who they are

00:02:10.309 --> 00:02:13.279
and that is so important

00:02:13.279 --> 00:02:14.719
in anybody's development

00:02:14.719 --> 00:02:16.339
and often with

00:02:16.339 --> 00:02:18.370
people with vision impairments

00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:23.359
it's difficult to get that feedback.
Next, raised line drawing boards are

00:02:23.359 --> 00:02:25.860
distributed to students seated around a
table.

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:30.870
First the narrator speaks then museum
instructor Leah Fox.  Artmaking need

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:32.680
not be complicated.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:35.989
Raised line drawing boards are a good way
to begin.

00:02:35.989 --> 00:02:40.949
A raised line drawing board is constructed
of a clipboard with a rubber surface

00:02:40.949 --> 00:02:42.829
covered by a plastic sheet.

00:02:42.829 --> 00:02:47.599
When writing on the plastic with a pen
the friction of the rubber against the

00:02:47.599 --> 00:02:50.089
plastic creates a raised surface,

00:02:50.089 --> 00:02:54.749
this way the artist can feel what they
have drawn. A boy holds up his drawing and beams.

00:02:56.330 --> 00:03:01.780
Then a raised line drawing of two pattern
dresses and a pair of high-heeled shoes.

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:05.800
